<!DOCTYPE html><html><head><title>$ command line ruby cheat sheets</title><link charset="utf-8" href="/style.css" media="screen" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" /></head><body><div class="main"><div class="header"><h1><a href="/">cheat sheets.</a></h1><code class="header">$ command line ruby cheat sheets</code></div></div><div class="content"><pre>1   % ls /user/dir/file.c
2   % which firefox
3   % make
4   % ./foo -f foo.conf
5   % vi foo.c bar.c

Getting stuff from the previous commands:
1	Previous command:        % !!  --&gt;% vi foo.c bar.c
2	Previous command:        % !-1 --&gt;% vi foo.c bar.c
3	Second previous command: % !-2 --&gt;% ./foo -f foo.conf

Getting individual arguments:
1	Last arg : % svn ci !$	       --&gt;% svn ci bar.c
2	All args : % svn ci !*	       --&gt;% svn ci foo.c bar.c
3	First arg: % svn ci !!:1       --&gt;% svn ci foo.c

Modifying commandlines
1   Head:       % !ls:$:h            --&gt;% /user/dir
2   Tail:       % !ls:$:t            --&gt;% file.c
3   Rm Suffix:  % !ls:$:r            --&gt;% /user/dir/file
4   Substitute: % !ls:$:s/user/dude/ --&gt;% /dude/dir/file.c

Note: a bang expression can be expanded with the tab key</pre></div><div class="clear"></div><div class="footer">Powered by <a href="http://www.sinatrarb.com/">Sinatra</a>,
